caption: A beautiful unassuming cathedral in the middle of Montmartre. It looks like a historical monument that hasn’t been overly maintained but has beautiful features such as high ceilings and stained glass.  It’s in a popular tourist area but doesn’t seem to attract as much attention as other cathedrals nearby.  Some nice religious iconography and relics on the inside.  I noticed on a poster they are doing gospel choir tonight, I’m sure it would look and sound amazing in there!
A was a nice quick stop on our stroll through Montmartre.  A nice cathedral with some old world architecture and charm.

I was visiting the Sacré Cœur and the Moulin Rouge and passed by this magnificent building. Entered and could see how beautifully preserved this church is. I am really becoming a fan of Paris churches and their architecture.  This place is so beautiful and peaceful, even in the surroundings of Montmartre, you can find silence here and peace. I fully recommend coming to this place.

Église Saint-Jean de Montmartre is a unique and lesser-known church located in the Montmartre district of Paris. Built at the turn of the 20th century, this church stands out for its distinctive architecture, blending Romanesque and Art Nouveau styles. Its striking façade, decorated with intricate details, and its interior, with colorful stained-glass windows and mosaics, create a serene and artistic atmosphere. The church is also notable for being one of the few in Paris constructed with reinforced concrete, a pioneering technique at the time. It offers a peaceful escape from the bustling streets of Montmartre, making it a hidden gem for visitors.

This doesn’t come up in any Paris “to-do” lists, but what a unique property with wood carvings paired with stained glass windows that offers quite an eerie feel in the evening. Would be wonderful to visit it in daytime when the light and shadow can play around with the wood.
It's the first time I've seen a church with this type of architecture, something that really caught my attention, it deserves a visit when you're visiting Montmartre.

Special church to visit, with a completely different style than the more well-known Sacre Coeur, also in Montmartre. Surprising that this church hasn't received nearly as much attention though it's style and decor, including the carved wood, is very interesting plus it has a peaceful ambiance conducive to reflection. Some areas have worn-away paint but it's well-maintained overall. Pretty seeing light streaming in through the stained glass windows, in contrast to the darker interior.

Saint-Jean de Montmartre is a Roman Catholic church located at 19 Rue des Abbesses in the 18th arrondissement. It is located next to Montmartre and is the first example of reinforced concrete in church construction.
A beautiful Art Nouveau Church with a spacious and graceful interior. Definitely worth a visit!

The exterior red brick of this church belies the wonder that are inside.   The reinforced concrete structure has been built into the hillside. There is wonderful wood work,  mosaics and vaulting inside.   The exterior does have minimal amounts of Art Deco elements,  apparently they ran out of funding. Neat stop when at the Place du Abesses at the foot of Montmartre.
Beautiful church with a lot of decor and wood structure. Probably overshadowed by Sacré-Coeur as not so popular. but worth a visit if like art Nouveau style while walking around Montmartre.

Great church in middle of Montmarte.  For me the best feature was the windows.  They were beautifully crafted and the light shines lovely colours into the church.

A cosy cathedral in art-nouveau style, situated right next to the metro station 'Abbesses'. Richly decorated with frescoes, it reminds of the old book with fairy tales. Is known for the depicting of Apocalypse riders, situated over the main entrance.

Church of Saint Jean de Montmartre is recognized by use of reinforced concrete in her construction.There is a guided tour of the church on every fourth Sunday of the month at 16:00 o'clock.The red brick facade is used for decoration as well as additional support an insulation.
